text=:Category: IndigenousLanguagesOfTheAmericas%0a:Expansion: How we were taught in school%0a:Author: AlexisA%0a:Original: [[Articles.Maskókî|Maskókî]] %0a:OriginalAuthor: [[Profiles.Connor_G|Connor_G]]%0a:Section: A%0a:Completed: 14.03.2021 - 13:03%0a:Status: ungraded%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeitem:)%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%0a%0a%25red%25 '''Grading History'''%0a%0a[[#history]]%0a%0a[[#historyend]]%0a%0a%25red%25 '''Comments to student'''%0a%0a[[#comments]]%0a%0a[[#commentsend]]%0a%0a----%0a----%0a!!%0a%0a%0a----%0a[[#content]]%0a%0aThis comment isn't necessarily specific to the Seminole Tribe, since (at least at my school) we were taught about "Native Americans" as a relatively uniform entity with hardly any distinction made between various tribes or regions (outside of maybe farming practices). This, itself, is a problem with the way American schools approach historical education about the indigenous because it is hardly fair to group such diverse entities together and pay only lip service to their unique characters.%0a%0aHowever, back to the topic at hand, I think that far too much education on Indigenous peoples, especially parts related to their languages, is framed in terms of "the past." As you mention in your post, the Seminoles formed as a legal entity less than a century ago and maintain their own languages to this day, but my school basically ended all education related to them at the Trail of Tears, leading to the false impression amongst many that they had been eradicated or conquered or otherwise cease to exist outside of small reservations.%0a%0a[[#contentends]]%0a----%0a(:Category:)%0a#foxbegin 210512-000936-574280#%0a!!Backup interface%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeExpansion:)%0a#foxend 210512-000936-574280#
